Seasonal temperature changes in Arctic Alaska

1 Overview

This project seeks to answer the following research question:

Is Arctic shrubification controlled by winter or summer temperatures?

1.1 Research Questions:

This analysis is composed of four subquestions:

  1. How has the mean July temperature of Arctic Alaska changed over the past 39 years (1979-2018)?

  2. How has the mean January temperature of Arctic Alaska changed over the past 39 years?

  3. Have winter or summer temperatures changed more over the study period?

  4. Are there any observable patterns of shrub expansion that can be explained by changes in winter or summer temperatures?

1.2 Rationale:

  • High latitude regions are projected to warm at twice the rate of the global average (IPCC 2013)
  • Permafrost thaw releases greenhouse gases & contributes to more warming
  • Shrubs are expanding & contribute to climate feedback cycles
    • Taller shrubs store more carbon - less carbon in atmosphere
    • Taller shrubs trap snow - soil is warmer during winter - increases permafrost thaw
  • In order to model changes in vegetation and climate we need a thorough understanding of ecosystem processes
  • However, the controls on shrub expansion are not well understood

1.3 Data:

NCEP-NCAR Reanalysis 1 (air.mon.mean)

Source: NCEP Reanalysis data provided by the NOAA/OAR/ESRL PSD, Boulder, Colorado, USA, from their Web site at https://www.esrl.noaa.gov/psd/

Note: this analysis was initally conducted using NCEP North American Regional Reanalysis (NARR) monthly temperature at 2m height, however the current dataset was ultimately selected because the NARR data is projected on an irregular grid which presented difficulties for spatial analysis.

1.4 Methodology:

  • Load and project shapefiles: World, Alaska, Alaskan Arctic
  • Load NetCDF4 File
  • Project temperature data
  • Plot long term mean temperature by month
  • Select region of interest and extract data
  • Index plot of January temperatures
  • Index plot of July temperatures

2 Load spatial data

2.1 Load packages

# load packages  
library(sf)

2.2 Load and project shapefiles

setwd('~/REarthSysSci')
# read the world shapefile
shp_path <- "~/REarthSysSci/gis/"
shp_name <- "ne_110m_admin_0_countries.shp"
shp_file <- paste(shp_path, shp_name, sep="")
world_shp <- read_sf(shp_file)
world_outline <- as(st_geometry(world_shp), Class="Spatial")

# read the Arctic shapefile
shp_name <- "alaska_arctic.shp"
shp_file <- paste(shp_path, shp_name, sep="")
arctic_shp <- read_sf(shp_file)
arctic_outline <- as(st_geometry(arctic_shp), Class="Spatial")

# read the Alaska shapefile
shp_name <- "alaska.shp"
shp_file <- paste(shp_path, shp_name, sep="")
alaska_shp <- read_sf(shp_file)
alaska_outline <- as(st_geometry(alaska_shp), Class="Spatial")

#project shapefiles

ak.proj <- "+proj=aea +lat_1=55 +lat_2=65 +lat_0=50 +lon_0=-154 +x_0=0 +y_0=0 +ellps=GRS80 +datum=NAD83 +units=m +no_defs"
arctic_proj <- spTransform(arctic_outline, CRS(ak.proj))
proj4string(world_outline) <- CRS("+proj=longlat")
world_proj <- spTransform(world_outline, CRS(ak.proj))
alaska_proj <- spTransform(alaska_outline, CRS(ak.proj))

5 Extract temperature data from Arctic Alaska

5.1 Subset temperature data based upon spatial selection

#subset the temperature data to focus on Arctic Alaska
arctic_buffer_75km <- st_buffer(arctic_shp, dist = 75000)

arctic_buffer_proj<-st_set_crs(arctic_buffer_75km, CRS(ak.proj))
arctic_buffer_proj<-as(st_geometry(arctic_buffer_proj), Class="Spatial")
arctic_buffer_proj <- spTransform(arctic_buffer_proj, CRS(ak.proj))

tmp_arctic<-mask(tmp_proj, arctic_buffer_proj)

5.2 Plot January 1979 temperature for the region

#rasterVis plot
mapTheme <- rasterTheme(region = rev(brewer.pal(10, "RdBu")))
cutpts <- c(-50,-40,-30,-20,-10,0,10,20,30,40,50)

plt + latticeExtra::layer(sp.lines(world_proj, col="black", lwd=1.0))+ latticeExtra::layer(sp.lines(arctic_proj, col="black", lwd=1.0))

5.3 Calculate monthly long-term mean temperatures for the Arctic

ncpath <- "/Users/Ori/Documents/REarthSysSci/"
ncname <- "arctic_tmp"  
ncfname <- paste(ncpath, ncname, ".nc", sep="")
dname <- "tmp"

# open a netCDF file
ncin <- nc_open(ncfname)


x <- ncvar_get(ncin,"lon")
xlname <- ncatt_get(ncin,"lon","long_name")
xunits <- ncatt_get(ncin,"lon","units")
nlon <- dim(x)


y <- ncvar_get(ncin,"lat")
ylname <- ncatt_get(ncin,"lat","long_name")
yunits <- ncatt_get(ncin,"lat","units")
nlat <- dim(y)



# get time
time <- ncvar_get(ncin,"time")
tunits <- ncatt_get(ncin,"time","units")
nt <- dim(time)

nm <- 12
ny <- nt/nm



# get years & generate months
year <- time/nm

month <- rep(seq(1:12), ny)


# get temperature
tmp_array <- ncvar_get(ncin,dname)
dlname <- ncatt_get(ncin,dname,"long_name")
dunits <- ncatt_get(ncin,dname,"units")
fillvalue <- ncatt_get(ncin,dname,"_FillValue")


# get global attributes
title <- ncatt_get(ncin,0,"title")
institution <- ncatt_get(ncin,0,"institution")
datasource <- ncatt_get(ncin,0,"source")
references <- ncatt_get(ncin,0,"references")
history <- ncatt_get(ncin,0,"history")
Conventions <- ncatt_get(ncin,0,"Conventions")

# close the netCDF file
nc_close(ncin)

# replace netCDF fill values with NA's
tmp_array[tmp_array==fillvalue$value] <- NA
#write arctic-region temperature data to new ncdf file

tmpin<-tmp_arctic
outfile <- "arctic_tmp.nc"
crs(tmpin) <- ak.proj 
writeRaster(tmpin, outfile, overwrite=TRUE, format="CDF", varname="tmp", varunit="degC", 
  longname="Monthly Mean Air Temperature at sigma level 0.995", xname="lon", yname="lat",zname="time",zunit="months since 1978-12" )
# get beginning obs of base period
begyr <- 1979; endyr <- 2018; nyrs <- endyr - begyr + 1
begobs <- 1
endobs <- 480
base_period <- paste(as.character(begyr)," - ", as.character(endyr), sep="")


# base-period array
tmp_array_base <- array(dim = c(nlon, nlat, nyrs * nm))

ny <- nyrs

tmp_array_base <- tmp_array[,, begobs:endobs]

# long-term means
tmp_ltm <- array(NA, dim = c(nlon, nlat, nm))


for (j in 1:nlon) {
  for (k in 1:nlat) {
    if (!is.na(tmp_array_base[j, k, 1])) {
      for (m in 1:nm)
        tmp_ltm[j, k, m] <- mean(tmp_array_base[j, k, seq(m, (m + nm*nyrs - 1), by=nm)])
    }
  }
}

5.4 Create a NetCDF of the Arctic mean temperature by month

#write mean annual temperature by month for arctic region
# netCDF file of ltm's

# path and file name, set dname
ncpath <- "/Users/Ori/Documents/REarthSysSci/"
ncname <- "air.mon.mean_ltm_arctic.nc"  
ncfname <- paste(ncpath, ncname, sep="")
dname <- "tmp_ltm"  # note: tmp means temperature (not temporary)

# get time values for output
time_out <- time[(begobs + (nyrs/2)*nm):(begobs + (nyrs/2)*nm + nm - 1)]
# recode NA's to fill_values
tmp_ltm[is.na(tmp_ltm)] <- fillvalue$value

# create and write the netCDF file -- ncdf4 version
# define dimensions
londim <- ncdim_def("lon","degrees_east",as.double(x)) 
latdim <- ncdim_def("lat","degrees_north",as.double(y)) 
timedim <- ncdim_def("time",tunits$value,as.double(time_out))

# define variables
dlname <- "Air Temperature at 2 m long-term mean"
tmp_def <- ncvar_def("tmp_ltm","degC",list(londim,latdim,timedim),fillvalue$value,dlname,prec="single")

# create netCDF file and put arrays
ncout <- nc_create(ncfname,tmp_def,force_v4=TRUE)

# put variables
ncvar_put(ncout,tmp_def,tmp_ltm)

# put additional attributes into dimension and data variables
ncatt_put(ncout,"lon","axis","X") #,verbose=FALSE) #,definemode=FALSE)
ncatt_put(ncout,"lat","axis","Y")
ncatt_put(ncout,"time","axis","T")
ncatt_put(ncout,"tmp_ltm","base_period", base_period)

# add global attributes
ncatt_put(ncout,0,"title",title$value)
ncatt_put(ncout,0,"institution",institution$value)
ncatt_put(ncout,0,"source",datasource$value)
ncatt_put(ncout,0,"references",references$value)
history <- paste("Ori Chafe", date(), sep=", ")
ncatt_put(ncout,0,"history",history)
ncatt_put(ncout,0,"Conventions",Conventions$value)



# close the file, writing data to disk
nc_close(ncout)

5.5 Calculate monthly temperature anomaly values in the Arctic

# calculate anomalies
tmp_anm <- array(NA, dim = c(nlon, nlat, nt))
tmp_anm <- tmp_array_base - rep(tmp_ltm, ny)

# create netCDF file of anomalies

# path and file name, set dname
ncpath <- "/Users/Ori/Documents/REarthSysSci/"
ncname <- "air.mon.mean_anm_arctic_test3.nc"  
ncfname <- paste(ncpath, ncname, sep="")
dname <- "tmp_anm"  # note: tmp means temperature (not temporary)

# recode NA's to fill_values
tmp_anm[is.na(tmp_anm)] <- fillvalue$value

# define dimensions
londim <- ncdim_def("lon","degrees_east",as.double(x)) 
latdim <- ncdim_def("lat","degrees_north",as.double(y)) 
timedim <- ncdim_def("time","months",as.double(time[1:480]))

# define variables
dlname <- "Air Temperature anomalies"
tmp_def <- ncvar_def("tmp_anm","degC",list(londim,latdim,timedim),fillvalue$value,dlname,prec="single")

# create netCDF file and put arrays
ncout <- nc_create(ncfname,tmp_def,force_v4=TRUE)

# put variables
ncvar_put(ncout,tmp_def,tmp_anm)

# put additional attributes into dimension and data variables
ncatt_put(ncout,"lon","axis","X") #,verbose=FALSE) #,definemode=FALSE)
ncatt_put(ncout,"lat","axis","Y")
ncatt_put(ncout,"time","axis","T")
ncatt_put(ncout,"tmp_anm","base_period", base_period)

# add global attributes
ncatt_put(ncout,0,"title",title$value)
ncatt_put(ncout,0,"institution",institution$value)
ncatt_put(ncout,0,"source",datasource$value)
ncatt_put(ncout,0,"references",references$value)
history <- paste("Ori Chafe", date(), sep=", ")
ncatt_put(ncout,0,"history",history)
ncatt_put(ncout,0,"Conventions",Conventions$value)

# close the file, writing data to disk
nc_close(ncout)

7 Plot temporal change in winter and summer temperatures

7.1 Create dataframe

date<-jul
value<-tmp_anm[14,4,jul]
jul_anm<-tmp_anm[14,4,jul]
tmp_df_jul <- data.frame(date,value)
tmp_df_jul[1]<-tmp_df_jul[1]/12 +1979
tmp_df_jul["month"]<-"July"

value<-tmp_anm[14,4,jan]
date<-jan
jan_anm<-tmp_anm[14,4,jan]
jan_anm<-jan_anm[1:39]
tmp_df_jan <- data.frame(date,value)
tmp_df_jan[1]<-tmp_df_jan[1]/12 +1979
tmp_df_jan["month"]<-"January"

janjul_df <- rbind(tmp_df_jan, tmp_df_jul)

7.2 Plot seasonal temperature anomalies and long-term trends

ggplot(janjul_df, aes(x=date, y=value, color = variable)) + geom_line(aes(x=date,y = value, col = month)) + geom_smooth(method = "lm",data=tmp_df_jul, size=1, color="red") + geom_smooth(method = "lm",data=tmp_df_jan, size=1, color="blue")+ theme_bw()+xlab("Year")+ylab("Temperature (degrees C)")+ggtitle("Interannual Variation and Seasonal Temperature Change") + scale_color_manual(name="State", 
                        labels = c("January","July"),
                        values = c("January"="blue","July"="red"))

8 Conclusion:

  • In the period from 1979 to 2018, both summer and winter temperatures in the Alaskan Arctic have increased.
  • Winter temperatures have increased at a greater rate than summer temperatures, and could potentially be increasing shrub expansion.
  • Additionally, in this region winter temperatures are more variable than summer temperatures.
